===Etymology===
Earliest extant attestation is in ''{{w|Discourses of the States}}'' (translated by {{zh-ref|Jacques, 2022b}}):
* {{zh-x|不然，^巴 ^浦 之 犀、犛{máo/lí}、兕、象，其 可 盡 乎，其 又 以 規 為{wéi} 瑱 也？|‘Otherwise, it is because rhinoceros, '''yaks''', wild bovids and elephants in Ba and Pu have become extinct, and for this reason you use my recommendations as earplugs (which are made from the bones of these exotic animals)?’|ref=Guoyu|collapsed=yes}}

According to {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}, pronunciation ''lí'' ←  {{och-l|犛|tr=*rə}} is either related to or borrowed from {{cog|bo|འབྲི||female yak}}, whose genuine cognate is {{cog|sit-tam}} ''*<sup>B</sup>prit'' ({{zh-ref|Jacques, d'Alpoim Guedes and Zhang, 2021}}). 

{{zh-ref|Jacques, d'Alpoim Guedes and Zhang (2021)}} also propose that pronunciation ''máo'' ← {{och-l|犛|tr=*mrˁu}} could reflect a borrowing from {{bor|zh|sit-rgy|-}} language after loss of final *''-ŋ'', thus making it cognate to Rgyalrongic terms for "male yak" like {{cog|sit-tsh|qɐ'''ⁿbrúʔ'''}}, {{cog|sit-zbu|qɐ'''ⁿbrúʔ'''}}, {{cog|sit-sit|kə'''mbrû'''}}, {{cog|sit-jap|qa'''mbrɯ'''}}, and {{cog|jiq|tr=ʁ'''brô'''}}, which in turn are cognates to {{cog|my|ပြောင်||‘gaur’ {{q|← ‘yak’}}}}, {{cog|bo|འབྲོང||wild yak}}, {{cog|sxg|tr= <sup>HL</sup>bõ|t= yak}}, {{cog|sit-nas-pro|*bru||yak}}, {{cog|sit-ers|-}} ''*bu'' "male yak", and possibly {{cog|mvm|tr=ndʐõ⁵³|t= male yak}} .

